from the stage because I quite

00:12:18.790 --> 00:12:23.360
like doing that, and that also
is an extraordinary piece,

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:25.650
and the Paris connection
there is, that last move,

00:12:25.650 --> 00:12:29.220
is the can-can, can-can macabre.

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:30.520
He's amazing, Tom.

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:34.800
I mean he just-he takes
things from everywhere.

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:36.620
He adores Faure like I do.

00:12:36.620 --> 00:12:38.610
I thought that was one of
the first bonds between us.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:41.490
That's partly why we became
friends because of our love of,

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.940
shared love of a late
Faure, but he takes it

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:46.930
from everywhere-[inaudible],
Janocek,

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:49.480
from jazz, from pop, everything.

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:53.970
He'll take anything, and it
comes out as his own language,

00:12:53.970 --> 00:12:56.540
and that's an extraordinary
gift for a composer.

00:12:56.540 --> 00:12:58.180
I think he just got it.

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:00.890
Some people have it,
and he does, I feel.

