try and get them in the door?

00:16:19.390 --> 00:16:21.380
&gt;&gt; Steven: Well, I wouldn't
call it art music for sure.

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:22.680
&gt;&gt; Nicholas: Well, classical.

00:16:22.680 --> 00:16:24.960
We're trying to move
on from that one.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:26.260
&gt;&gt; Steven: No, no.

00:16:26.260 --> 00:16:27.560
&gt;&gt; Nicholas: Good music.

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:28.860
How about that?

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:30.160
&gt;&gt; Steven: I'd say you're going

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:31.460
to hear stories basically,
I mean, especially.

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:32.760 position:56%
Actually, it's a good thing to start
with a Shostakovich because it's

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:35.190
like a ballad, the first
particularly, but the whole piece,

00:16:35.190 --> 00:16:37.670
it's like a collection of stories,

00:16:37.670 --> 00:16:41.730
and I mean that actually
goes for every piece tonight.

00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:45.560
Perhaps in a way the Faure a little
bit less, but it's different.

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:49.240
It's more sort of a portrait of
nature, the [inaudible] ones, but,

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:54.220
yeah, I would say you're
going to hear humor

00:16:54.220 --> 00:16:56.250
or you're going to hear drama.

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:58.620
You're going to hear
exquisite beauty.

00:16:58.620 --> 00:17:03.250
I mean in the music, not
the playing, I would say,

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:04.670
and you're going to hear a range

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:09.350
of voices telling you this
very, very different story.

00:17:09.350 --> 00:17:12.250
