00:19:46.980 --> 00:19:51.380
&gt;&gt; Audience: Hi, Steven.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:52.680
&gt;&gt; Steven: Hi.

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:54.030
&gt;&gt; Audience: So I was wondering
when you are approaching a piece

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:56.670
for the first time
and say it's something

00:19:56.670 --> 00:20:01.530
with piano or-I don't know how
if you're a piano player as well,

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:04.090
but how do you study
the classical scene?

00:20:04.090 --> 00:20:08.040
So I always have this problem of-I
focused on my part, but then I kind

00:20:08.040 --> 00:20:10.010
of forget what's going
on at the piano,

00:20:10.010 --> 00:20:14.740
and a lot of your musical
advice, I think, to all musicians,

00:20:14.740 --> 00:20:18.950
and you're always emphasizing that
like the story that's going back

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:20.250
and forth between those things.

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:23.470
So I was wondering how you if
you're coming into something cold,

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:30.000
how you kind of integrate
kind of both voices?

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.670
&gt;&gt; Steven: Well, I deal
with that in the book.

00:20:31.670 --> 00:20:36.030
I say that every musician
really should play the piano

00:20:36.030 --> 00:20:38.600
because you have to
know the whole score.

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:40.570
You have to know the
piano part and, you know,

00:20:40.570 --> 00:20:42.460
how ever many parts there are,
you have to know them all.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:45.830
Otherwise you're like an actor
only knowing one part in a play,

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:49.370
and so you're not going
to get the story.

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:51.440 position:56%
So, yeah, I work a lot at the piano.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:52.740
It takes me hours often.

00:20:52.740 --> 00:20:54.820
I just play, and it
makes such a difference.

00:20:54.820 --> 00:20:56.120
Well, it makes all the difference.

00:20:56.120 --> 00:20:57.850
I couldn't really learn
a piece without.

00:20:57.850 --> 00:21:01.350
Occasionally if it's a
[inaudible] modern score

00:21:01.350 --> 00:21:04.590
and it's just too complicated,
then I unwillingly have to listen

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:06.940
to a recording, but
I'd much rather not.

00:21:06.940 --> 00:21:09.020
But no, absolutely.

00:21:09.020 --> 00:21:10.320
Go to the piano with songs.

00:21:10.320 --> 00:21:11.710
Absolutely, go to the piano.

00:21:11.710 --> 00:21:13.220
Yeah. Understand the harmonies

00:21:13.220 --> 00:21:15.550
because that's what the
composer was thinking about,

00:21:15.550 --> 00:21:17.910
and ask yourself first of
all what has he written?

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:20.970
You need a good edition always,
and that makes a huge difference,

00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:24.210
and then why has he
written or she written it,

00:21:24.210 --> 00:21:25.850
written it, written that?

00:21:25.850 --> 00:21:27.220
Every marking there's a reason.

00:21:27.220 --> 00:21:30.490
The composer's hands don't just
twitch and they write a piano

00:21:30.490 --> 00:21:32.410
or an [inaudible] or
an accent or whatever.

00:21:32.410 --> 00:21:37.860
They mean it, and, yes, it's fun
to get the sort of little messages

00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:41.080
from the gentleman behind the
screen there, Mr. Beethoven.

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:42.380
Hundreds of years.

00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:44.850
Every marking he puts
makes such a difference

00:21:44.850 --> 00:21:46.590
if you actually look at it.

00:21:46.590 --> 00:21:47.950
Try to think what he wrote.

00:21:47.950 --> 00:21:50.830
As my friend Olli Mustonen
says, "These are messages

00:21:50.830 --> 00:21:55.710
from one good musician to
another," and I like that.

00:21:55.710 --> 00:22:02.450
He also came out with
a great-Oh, yes.

00:22:02.450 --> 00:22:04.910
[Applause] Thank you.

